The result showed that the cytotoxicity of CDs in intro was very low (Fig. S4), and the cell viability remained greater than 95% even if incubated with a relatively high concentration of CDs (2.5mg/mL), demonstrating the excellent biocompatibility of CDs. Furthermore, most of CDs presented in the cytoplasmic area (
                        Fig. S5
                        ), suggesting that the as-prepared CDs are potential for cytoplasm staining (He et al., 2015). Bright field imaging in Fig. S5a is possibly related to the different protein and lipid density, water content and sample thickness (Majzner et al., 2012). The blue fluorescent area overlapped at the locations of the cells (Fig. S5b), indicating that CDs could be uptaken and accumulated in HEp-2 cells. Importantly, the dark area in cell is considered as the cell nucleus, which could draw the conclusion that CDs can smoothly penetrate into the cells by endocytosis (Fan et al., 2014) and mainly located in the cytoplasm (Liu et al., 2015; Zhang et al., 2012), owing to the small size (<5nm) as well as the good biocompatibility of CDs. The merged imaging further supports the idea that CDs mainly located in the cytoplasm (Liu et al., 2015; Zhang et al., 2012). The reconstructed three dimensional (3D) cell imaging is presented within an xyz-coordination system (Fig. S5d). By viewing the volume option and the xy-, zy- and xz-plane, it was possible to obtain a 3D cross-section of the cell. 3D imaging parameters were set to a pixel size of 21µm, 21µm and 7µm in x, y and z, respectively, which indicated that the as-prepared CDs present excellent endocytosis ability and have the potential of a promising fluorescent nanoprobe in cells.
